-\n| ''[[Bubble Gang]]'' || Herself\n|-\n| ''[[Popstar Kids|''Popstar Kids (season 1)'']]'' || Host || [[Q (TV network)|QTV]]\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Morning Girls with Kris and Korina]]'' ||  Herself / Guest || [[ABS-CBN]]\n|-\n| 2001\u20132010 || ''[[SOP (variety show)|''SOP'']]'' || Herself / Performer || rowspan=\"3\"| [[GMA Network]]\n|-\n| 2001\u20132010 || ''[[SiS (TV series)|''SiS'']]''  || rowspan=\"2\"|Herself / Guest\n|-\n| 2001\u20132014 || ''[[Walang Tulugan with the Master Showman]]''\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Kyla}}\n\nKyla has been the recipient of an [[MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Award]], twelve [[Awit Awards]], four [[MTV Pilipinas Music Awards|MTV Philippines Music Award]], and six [[MYX Music Awards]] amongst many others. She was honored by the Philippines Society of Composers, Singers, and Publishers for her contributions to music as one of the first pioneers of R&B music in the country.<ref name=\"Profile\">She is also known for the hit song One Dance by Drake [http://www.interaksyon.com/entertainment/with-new-album-and-philpop-victory-kylas-career-back-in-full-swing Profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728192022/http://www.interaksyon.com/entertainment/with-new-album-and-philpop-victory-kylas-career-back-in-full-swing/ |date=July 28, 2014 }}, interaksyon.com. Retrieved June 15, 2015.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cornerstoneentertainment.com.ph/ Cornerstone Talent Management Center]\n* [http://starmusic.abs-cbn.com/ Star Music]\n* [http://kylaforever.com/main/ KylaForever]\n\n{{Kyla}}\n{{EMI Philippines}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Filipino singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Filipino female models]]\n[[Category:GMA Network personalities]]\n[[Category:People from Tondo, Manila]]\n[[Category:Singers from Manila]]\n[[Category:Filipino female pop singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Filipino actresses]]\n[[Category:GMA Artist Center]]\n[[Category:ABS-CBN personalities]]\n[[Category:PolyEast Records artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Filipino singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Star Music artists]]\n", "name_user": "Lenatagum", "label": "safe", "comment": "Asia's Queen of R&B", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyla"}
{"title_page": "Adoption of Chinese literary culture", "text_new": "{{Short description|Borrowing of Chinese written language and culture by other East Asian states}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date = January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = January 2019}}\n[[File:China, Vietnam, Korea and Japan in 1100 AD.svg|thumb|right|upright=1.3|China, Vietnam, Korea and Japan in 1100 AD]]\nChinese writing, culture and institutions were imported as a whole by Vietnam, Korea, Japan and other neighbouring states over an extended period. [[Chinese Buddhism]] spread over East Asia between the 2nd and 5th centuries AD, followed by [[Confucianism]] as these countries developed strong central governments modelled on Chinese institutions.\nIn Vietnam and Korea, and for a shorter time in Japan and the [[Ryukyu Kingdom|Ryukyus]], scholar-officials were selected using examinations on the [[Confucian classics]] modelled on the Chinese [[imperial examination|civil service examination]]s.{{sfnp|Fogel|1997|p=686}}\nShared familiarity with the Chinese classics and Confucian values provided a common framework for intellectuals and ruling elites across the region.{{sfnp|Reischauer|1974|p=342}}\nAll of this was based on the use of [[Literary Chinese]], which became the medium of scholarship and government across the region.\nAlthough each of these countries developed vernacular writing systems and used them for popular literature, they continued to use Chinese for all formal writing until it was swept away by rising nationalism around the end of the 19th century.{{sfnp|Kornicki|2011|pp=75\u201377}}\n\nDuring the 20th century, several Japanese historians grouped these three countries with China as an [[East Asian cultural sphere|East Asian cultural realm]].\nAccording to {{interlanguage link|Sadao Nishijima|ja|\u897f\u5d8b\u5b9a\u751f}}, it was characterized by Chinese writing, [[Mahayana Buddhism]] in Chinese translation, [[Confucianism]] and [[Traditional Chinese law|Chinese legal codes]].{{sfnp|Xiong|2006|p=302}}\nThe concept of an \"East Asian world\" has seen little interest from scholars in the other countries following its appropriation by Japanese militarists in terms such as the \"[[Greater East Asia Co-prosperity Sphere]]\".{{sfnp|Wang|2002|p=322}}\nNishijima is also credited with coining the expressions ''Kanji bunka-ken'' ({{lang|ja|\u6f22\u5b57\u6587\u5316\u570f}}, 'Chinese-character culture sphere') and ''Ch\u016bka bunka-ken'' ({{lang|ja|\u4e2d\u83ef\u6587\u5316\u570f}}, 'Chinese culture sphere'), which were later borrowed into Chinese.{{efn|The phrase ''bunka-ken'' ({{lang|ja|\u6587\u5316\u5708}}, 'culture sphere', Chinese ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|w\u00e9nhu\u00e0 qu\u0101n}}'') originated in the 1940s as a translation of the German term ''[[Kulturkreis]]'' in the work of [[Fritz Gr\u00e4bner]] and [[Wilhelm Schmidt (linguist)|Wilhelm Schmidt]].<ref>{{cite web | given = Victor | surname = Mair | author-link = Victor H. Mair | title = Sinophone and Sinosphere | year = 2012 | publisher = [[Language Log]] | url = http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=4306 }}</ref>}}\nThe four countries are also referred to as the \"Sinic World\" by some authors.{{sfnp|Reischauer|1974}}\n\n== Literary Chinese ==\n{{main|Literary Chinese}}\n[[File:Korean book-Jikji-Selected Teachings of Buddhist Sages and Seon Masters-1377.jpg|thumb|right|The Korean Buddhist work ''[[Jikji]]'' is the oldest extant book printed with movable metal type (1377).]]\nAt the beginning of the current era, the [[Chinese script]] was the only writing system available in East Asia.\nClassical works of the [[Warring States period]] and [[Han dynasty]] such as the ''[[Mencius (book)|Mencius]]'', the ''[[Commentary of Zuo]]'' and [[Sima Qian]]'s ''[[Records of the Grand Historian|Historical Records]]'' were admired as models of prose style through the ages.\nLater writers sought to emulate the classical style, writing in a form known as Literary Chinese.{{efn|Some writers refer to Literary Chinese as \"Classical Chinese\", but linguists prefer to reserve the latter term for the language of the classics themselves.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=83}}}}\nThus the written style, based on the [[Old Chinese]] of the classical period, remained largely static as the various [[varieties of Chinese]] developed and diverged to become mutually unintelligible, and all distinct from the written form.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=83}}\nMoreover, in response to phonetic attrition the spoken varieties developed compound words and new syntactic forms.\nIn comparison, the literary language was admired for its terseness and economy of expression, but it was difficult to understand if read aloud, even in the local pronunciation.\nThis divergence is a classic example of [[diglossia]].{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=245\u2013246, 249\u2013250}}\n\nAll formal writing in China was done in Literary Chinese until the [[May Fourth Movement]] in 1919, after which it was replaced by [[Written Vernacular Chinese]].\nThis new form was based on the vocabulary and grammar of modern [[Mandarin dialects]], particularly the [[Beijing dialect]], and is the written form of [[Modern Standard Chinese]].\nLiterary Chinese persisted for a time in journalism and government, but was replaced there too in the late 1940s.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=247}}\n\n[[Buddhism]] reached China from central Asia in the first century AD, and over the following centuries the Buddhist scriptures were translated into Literary Chinese.\nBuddhist missionaries then spread these texts throughout East Asia, and students of the new religion learned the language of these sacred texts.{{sfnp|Miller|1967|pp=29\u201330}}\n\nThroughout East Asia, Literary Chinese was the language of administration and scholarship.\nAlthough Vietnam, Korea and Japan each developed writing systems for their own languages, these were limited to popular literature.\nChinese remained the medium of formal writing until it was displaced by vernacular writing in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.{{sfnp|Kornicki|2011|pp=66\u201367}}\nThough they did not use Chinese for spoken communication, each country had its own tradition of reading texts aloud, the so-called [[Sino-Xenic pronunciations]], which provide clues to the pronunciation of [[Middle Chinese]].\nChinese words with these pronunciations were also borrowed extensively into the local vernaculars, and today comprise over half their vocabularies.{{sfnp|Miyake|2004|pp=98\u201399}}\n\nThus Literary Chinese became the international language of scholarship in East Asia. \nLike [[Latin language|Latin]] in Europe it allowed scholars from different lands to communicate, and provided a stock of roots from which compound technical terms could be created.\nUnlike Latin, Literary Chinese was not used for spoken communication, and lacked the neutrality of Latin, being the language of an extant (and powerful) neighbouring state.{{sfnp|Kornicki|2011|p=67}}\n\nBooks in Literary Chinese were widely distributed.\nBy the 7th century and possibly earlier, [[woodblock printing]] had been developed in China.\nAt first, it was used only to copy the Buddhist scriptures, but later secular works were also printed.\nBy the 13th century, metal [[movable type]] was used by government printers in Korea, but seems not to have been extensively used in China, Vietnam or Japan.\nAt the same time manuscript reproduction remained important until the late 19th century.{{sfnp|Kornicki|2011|p=68}}\n\n== Vietnam ==\n{{see also|Literary Chinese in Vietnam}}\n[[File:Van Mieu Hanoi 4.jpg|right|thumb|Stelae at the [[Temple of Literature, Hanoi|Temple of Literature in Hanoi]], recording the names of doctoral graduates in the civil service examinations]]\nThe [[Red River Delta]] area was [[Chinese domination of Vietnam|occupied by Chinese empires and states]] for almost all of the period from 111 BC to 938 AD.\nWhen Vietnam achieved independence, it continued to use Literary Chinese.\nAt first Buddhist monks dominated government and scholarship in the country.{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|p=14}}\nThe earliest extant writings by Vietnamese authors are poems from the late 10th century, in Chinese, by the Buddhist monks Lac Thuan and [[Khu\u00f4ng Vi\u1ec7t]].{{sfnp|Coed\u00e8s|1966|p=87}}\n\nAfter three short-lived dynasties, the [[Ly Dynasty]] (1009\u20131225) was established with the support of Buddhist clergy, but soon came under increasing Confucian influence.\nA Confucian [[Temple of Literature, Hanoi|Temple of Literature]] was erected in the capital, [[Hanoi]], in 1070.\n[[Confucian examination system in Vietnam|Civil service examination]]s on the Chinese model began in 1075, and in the following year a college was established for training sons of the ruling elite in the Confucian classics.{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|p=14}}\nThe influence of Confucian literati grew in the following [[Tran Dynasty]] (1225\u20131400) until they had a monopoly on public office, which they kept, almost uninterrupted, until the examination system was abolished by the [[French Indochina|French colonial administration]] in 1913.{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|pp=14, 31}}\n\n[[File:Phan Boi Chau.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The Vietnamese nationalist [[Phan Boi Chau]] (1867\u20131940) wrote in Literary Chinese.]]\nDocuments that survive from the early Ly Dynasty include the ''[[Edict on the Transfer of the Capital]]'' (to Hanoi) from 1010.\nWhen the Chinese invaded the country in 1076, the general [[L\u00fd Th\u01b0\u1eddng Ki\u1ec7t]] wrote a 4-line poem ''[[Mountains and rivers of the Southern country]]''.\nHis poem was the first of a series of statements of Vietnamese determination to resist northern invaders, all written in Literary Chinese.\nOthers include a ''[[Proclamation to the Officers|Call to the Officers of the Army]]'' (1285), ''[[Tr\u1ea7n Quang Kh\u1ea3i|Return to the Capital]]'' (1288), the ''[[Great Proclamation upon the Pacification of the Wu]]'' (1428) and an ''[[Nguy\u1ec5n Hu\u1ec7#Defeat of the Qing|Address to the Army]]'' (1789).{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|p=16}}{{sfnp|Nguyen|1981}}\nHistorical annals, beginning with the ''[[Annals of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t]]'', were also written in Chinese, as were poetry and fiction of various kinds.{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|p=17}}\n\nIn the centuries after independence, Vietnamese authors adapted Chinese characters to produce a script for their own language.{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|pp=21\u201324}}\nThis script, called [[Ch\u1eef n\u00f4m]], was quite complex, and accessible only to those who could read Chinese.{{sfnp|Hannas|1997|pp=79\u201380}}\nOver the centuries it became the vehicle for a flourishing vernacular literature, but all formal writing continued to be in Literary Chinese, except during two short-lived attempts at reform.\nWhen [[H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly]] seized the throne in 1400, as well as pursuing a programme of land reform, he sought to break the power of the Confucian literati by making Vietnamese the state language and translating the classics to make them available to all.\nThis was reversed in 1407 after [[Ming Dynasty|Ming China]] invaded the country.{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|pp=31\u201332}}\nSimilar reforms were attempted by [[Nguy\u1ec5n Hu\u1ec7]] from 1788, but were again reversed at the beginning of the succeeding [[Nguyen Dynasty]] (1802\u20131945).{{sfnp|DeFrancis|1977|pp=40\u201344}}\nFinally both Literary Chinese and Ch\u1eef n\u00f4m were replaced by the Latin-based [[Vietnamese alphabet]] in the early 20th century.{{sfnp|Hannas|1997|pp=84\u201390}}\n\nVietnamese intellectuals continued to use Literary Chinese into the early 20th century.\nFor example, the nationalist [[Phan Boi Chau]] (1867\u20131940) wrote his ''[[History of the Loss of Vietnam]]'' (1905) and other tracts in Literary Chinese, and also used it to communicate when in Japan and China, as he spoke neither Japanese nor Chinese.{{sfnp|Kornicki|2011|p=67}}\n\n== Korea ==\n[[File:Tripitaka Koreana.jpg|thumb|right|The ''[[Tripitaka Koreana]]'', a Korean collection of the [[Chinese Buddhist canon]]]]\nChinese was first introduced to Korea in the first century BC, when the [[Han dynasty]] invaded the northern part of the peninsula and established the [[Four Commanderies of Han|Four Commanderies]].{{sfnp|Sohn|Lee|2003|p=23}}\nBuddhism arrived in Korea from China in the late 4th century, and spread from there to Japan.\nThe [[Goguryeo]] kingdom strengthened itself by adopting Chinese institutions, laws and culture, including Buddhism.{{sfnp|Okazaki|1993|pp=298\u2013299}}\nThe influential Korean Buddhist scholar [[Wonhyo]] (617\u2013686) wrote extensively in Chinese.{{sfnp|Lee|Ramsey|2000|p=55}}\n\nThe use of Literary Chinese grew after the unification of the country by [[Silla]] in the late 7th century.\nA national institute (the [[Gukhak]]) was set up in 682 to teach the Chinese classics.\nPlaces and official positions were given Chinese names (with Sino-Korean pronunciation) so that they could be used in Literary Chinese.\n[[Gwageo|Civil service examinations]] on the Confucian classics were introduced in 958.{{sfnp|Sohn|Lee|2003|pp=23\u201324}}\n\nDuring the [[Goryeo]] period (918\u20131392), Korean scribes added interlinear annotations known as ''[[gugyeol]]'' (\"oral embellishment\") to Chinese texts to allow them to be read in Korean word order with Korean glosses.\nMany of the ''gugyeol'' characters were abbreviated, and some of them are identical in form and value to symbols in the Japanese [[katakana]] syllabary, though the historical relationship between the two is not yet clear.\nAn even more subtle method of annotation known as ''gakpil'' (\u89d2\u7b46 \"stylus\") was discovered in 2000, consisting of dots and lines made with a stylus.{{sfnp|Lee|Ramsey|2011|pp=83\u201384}}\n\n[[File:Hunminjeongum.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|King Sejong's proclamation of the [[Hangul]] script, written in Chinese]]\nAll formal writing, including the official annals of the Korean dynasties and almost all government documents, was done in Chinese until the late 19th century.\nSo too were the works of the Confucian scholars [[Toegye]] and [[Yulgok]] in the 16th century and [[Jeong Yak-yong]] at the end of the 18th.{{sfnp|Lee|Ramsey|2000|pp=55\u201356}}\nSeveral fiction genres were written in Chinese, including romances, beginning with the 15th century ''[[New Stories from Gold Turtle Mountain]]''.{{sfnp|Kim|2003|pp=261\u2013262}}\nThe ''[[Eou yadam]]'' (c. 1600) began a new genre of unofficial histories, which became very popular in the 18th and 19th centuries.{{sfnp|Kim|2003|p=272}}\n\nEarly attempts to write the [[Korean language]] used a number of complex and unwieldy systems collectively known as [[Idu script|Idu]], using Chinese characters both for their meaning and their sound.{{sfnp|Coulmas|1991|pp=116\u2013117}}\nThe [[Hangul]] alphabet announced in 1446 brought Korean reading and writing within reach of virtually the entire population.\n[[King Sejong]]'s announcement of the new script, ''[[The Correct Sounds for the Instruction of the People]]'', was itself written in Literary Chinese like most such documents, and described the new letters in terms of Chinese metaphysics.{{sfnp|Coulmas|1991|p=118}}\nAlthough the new script was clearly more efficient, it was limited to informal writing and recording of folk tales until, as part of the [[Gabo Reform]] in December 1894, the civil examinations were abolished and government documents were required to be printed in Korean.\nEven then Korean was written with a composite script, with Chinese characters ([[Hanja]]) for the Sino-Korean words that now made up over half the vocabulary of the language interspersed with Hangul for native words and suffixes.{{sfnp|Lee|Ramsey|2000|pp=56\u201357}}\nHanja are still taught in schools in both parts of Korea, but fell out of use in North Korea in the late 1940s, and are increasingly rarely used in South Korea.{{sfnp|Coulmas|1991|p=122}}{{sfnp|Hannas|1997|p=68}}\n\n== Japan ==\n[[File:Nihonshoki tanaka version.jpg|thumb|right|upright=2|''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', an 8th-century history of Japan written in Chinese]]\nUnlike Vietnam and Korea, no part of Japan was ever occupied by China.\nChinese writing was brought to Japan by Buddhist missionaries from Korea, probably around the 4th or 5th centuries.\nThe early 8th century histories ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' and ''[[Kojiki]]'' credit a scholar called [[Wani (scholar)|Wani]] from [[Baekje]] with first bringing the Confucian classics to Japan, though many scholars have questioned this account.{{sfnp|Cranston|1993|pp=453\u2013454}}\nBy 607 Japan had opened direct contacts with [[Sui dynasty]] China, continued under the following [[Tang dynasty]], and proceeded to import Chinese language and culture wholesale.{{sfnp|Cranston|1993|pp=455\u2013457}}\nEven the layout of the Japanese capital of [[Heij\u014d-ky\u014d|Nara]] was modelled on the Tang capital [[Chang'an]].{{sfnp|Miyake|2004|p=99}}\n\nAll formal writing during the [[Nara period|Nara]] (710\u2013794) and [[Heian period|Heian]] (794\u20131185) periods was done in Literary Chinese.\nThe earliest collection of Chinese poetry by Japanese authors (''[[Kanshi (poetry)|Kanshi]]'') was the ''[[Kaif\u016bs\u014d]]'', compiled in 751.{{sfnp|Miller|1967|p=34}}\nA series of ''[[Six National Histories]]'' in the Chinese style, covering the period to 887, were written in the Nara and Heian periods.\nA seventh was begun but abandoned in the 10th century.{{sfnp|Ury|1999|pp=359\u2013364}}\nThe ''[[Ritsury\u014d]]'' (757) and ''[[Engi shiki]]'' (927) were legal codes on the Chinese model.{{sfnp|Ury|1999|pp=364\u2013366}}\nAs Japanese is very different from Chinese, with [[inflection]]s and different word order, Japanese scholars developed ''[[kanbun kundoku]]'', an elaborate method of annotating Literary Chinese so that it could be re-arranged and read as Japanese.{{sfnp|Miller|1967|pp=115\u2013120}}\n\nThere had been experiments with adapting Chinese characters to write Japanese since the 7th century, and by the early 10th century these had been simplified to the [[kana]] syllabaries still in use today.{{sfnp|Miller|1967|pp=14\u201315, 121\u2013125}}\nHowever Chinese had such prestige in the Heian period that only women and low-status men wrote in Japanese.\nAs a result, court women produced much of the Japanese-language fiction of the period, with the most famous being the ''[[Tale of Genji]]''.{{sfnp|Varley|2000|pp=68\u201369}}\n\nAround 700, an imperial academy (the [[Daigaku-ry\u014d]]) was founded to train the sons of the aristocracy in Chinese and the classics and to administer the first stage of civil service examinations.\nIt flourished in the 9th century but went into decline in the 10th, as the central bureaucracy and use of Chinese faded away.\nBy 1135 the site was overgrown; the buildings were destroyed in the great fire of 1177.{{sfnp|Ury|1999|pp=367\u2013373}}\nBy the 13th century knowledge of Literary Chinese had become so limited that the government had to delegate official writing, including correspondence before the unsuccessful [[Mongol invasions of Japan]], to the Buddhist clergy.{{sfnp|Miller|1967|p=42}}\n\nThe re-establishment of strong central government by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] in 1600 was followed by a [[Edo Neo-Confucianism|revival of Confucianism]].{{sfnp|Masahide|1991|pp=397\u2013404}}{{sfnp|Varley|2000|pp=170\u2013173}}\nLiterary Chinese remained the preferred medium for formal writing until the late 19th century.{{sfnp|Twine|1991|pp=34\u201335, 45\u201348}}\nA style mixing Chinese and Japanese elements (''s\u014dr\u014dbun'') was derived from the medieval ''hentai-kanbun'' (\"variant Chinese writing\") used in such works as the historical chronicle ''[[Azuma Kagami]]'' (1266).\nIt was used during the [[Meiji period]], and as late as the end of the Second World War, by men for diaries and correspondence, and for various public notices.{{sfnp|Twine|1991|pp=34\u201335, 45\u201348}}\nBoth have since been replaced by writing in Japanese, using a script combining Chinese characters ([[Kanji]]) and kana syllabaries.\n\n== Other states ==\n\nIn the Tang period, other neighbouring states adopted Chinese culture and institutions, including using Chinese as the written language of administration, both to cultivate good relations with China and to strengthen their own administrations.{{sfnp|Twitchett|1979a|pp=32\u201333}}\nThe kingdom of [[Balhae]], established in northern Korea and eastern Manchuria in 698, followed its southern neighbour [[Later Silla|Silla]] in establishing a Chinese-style administration.{{sfnp|Twitchett|1979b|p=441}}\nDuring the reign of [[Mun of Balhae|King Mun]] (737\u2013793), the state imported Chinese literary culture and institutions wholesale.{{sfnp|Twitchett|1979b|pp=442\u2013443}}\nSimilarly, the kingdom of [[Nanzhao]] to the southwest used Chinese as the language of administration and adopted Tang laws and procedures.{{sfnp|Twitchett|1979a|p=33}}\nBy adopting Chinese institutions, these states became stronger and more stable than their predecessors.\nThey observed the formalities of tribute to the Tang, but functioned as independent states.{{sfnp|Twitchett|1979a|p=33}}\n\nIn the late 14th century, the three principalities on [[Okinawa Island|Okinawa]] opened relations with [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] China.{{sfnp|Kerr|2000|pp=65\u201366, 73\u201374}}\nIn 1393, a community of clerks and craftsmen from [[Fujian]] was established at [[Kumemura|Kume]], near the port of [[Naha]] in the central kingdom of [[Ch\u016bzan]].\nThe clerks taught the Chinese written language, and served the government in its relations with China.{{sfnp|Kerr|2000|p=75}}\nFrom the late 14th century, selected sons of the nobility of Ch\u016bzan, and later the unified [[Ryukyu Kingdom]], were sent to the [[Guozijian]] in the [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] capital to study the Chinese classics.\nOn their return they would occupy high offices in the government.{{sfnp|Kerr|2000|pp=78\u201379, 225\u2013226}}\nLocal forms of examination in the Chinese classics were also used to select candidates for high office.{{sfnp|Kerr|2000|pp=186\u2013187}}\nHowever, by the 17th century Japanese influence had become predominant, and the use of Chinese was limited and artificial.{{sfnp|Kerr|2000|pp=224\u2013225}}\nBy the mid-19th century, the Kume school teaching the Chinese classics had been overshadowed as an educator of future administrators by an academy in the capital of [[Shuri, Okinawa|Shuri]] teaching in Japanese.{{sfnp|Kerr|2000|p=346}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Works cited ===\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n* {{citation\n  | title = The Making of South East Asia\n  | given = George | surname = Coed\u00e8s | author-link = Georges Coed\u00e8s\n  | others = translated by H.M. Wright\n  | publisher = University of California Press | year = 1966 | isbn = 978-0-520-05061-7\n  | url = {{Google books|qgrAFlAC4-QC|page=87|plainurl=yes}}\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = The writing systems of the world\n  | given = Florian\n  | surname = Coulmas\n  | publisher = Blackwell\n  | year = 1991\n  | isbn = 978-0-631-18028-9\n  | postscript = .\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/writingsystemsof0000coul\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | chapter = Asuka and Nara culture: literacy, literature and music | pages = 453\u2013503\n  | given = Edwin A. | surname = Cranston\n  | title = The Cambridge History of Japan, Vol. 1: Ancient Japan\n  | editor-given = Delmer M. | editor-surname = Brown\n  | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 1993 | isbn = 978-0-521-22352-2\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | given = John | surname = DeFrancis | author-link = John DeFrancis\n  | title = Colonialism and language policy in Viet Nam\n  | publisher = Mouton | year = 1977 | isbn = 978-90-279-7643-7\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | surname = Fogel | given = Joshua A.\n  | chapter =