{"title_page": "KK (singer)", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| image            = KK AIIC Bangalore 2016.jpg\n| caption          = KK Performing Live at Alive India in Concert, [[Bangalore]], [[India]] in Jan \n\n| name             = Krishnakumar Kunnath\n| native_name      = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Krishnakumar Kunnath\n| alias            = KK, K.K., Kay Kay\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = Delhi, India\n| death_date       = \n| instrument       = Vocal\n| genre            = [[playback singer|Playback singing]], [[Indian pop|Indipop]], rock\n| occupation       = Singer, composer and lyricist\n| years_active     = 1996\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://themesmerizer.com/ Official web page of KK]</span><br />\n<span class=\"plainlinks\">[https://facebook.com/profile.php?id=92224051219 KK on Facebook]</span><br />\n<span class=\"plainlinks\">[https://twitter.com/K_K_Pal KK on Twitter]</span>\n| Alma mater       = [[Kirori Mal College]]\n}}\n\n'''Krishnakumar Kunnath''' (popularly known as '''KK''', '''K.K.''' or '''Kay Kay''') is an Indian singer. He is a prominent singer in [[Hindi]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Kannada]], [[Malayalam]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] languages films.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/the-right-note/article3204274.ece |title= The right note|date= 9 December 2006 |work=[[The Hindu]] |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> KK is noted for his clear and soothing voice; broad vocal range and noteplay. He is considered as one of the most versatile singers of [[India]].<ref name=\"Indie\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indicine.com/movies/bollywood/best-kk-songs-top-10/|title=Best KK songs-Top 10|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> . His [https://www.lyricsmust.com/ date] Of Birth Is 23 August 1968. His Zodiac Sign Is Virgo.\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:KK's source of energy.JPG|thumb|KK with his wife Jyothy, son Nakul Krishna and daughter Taamara<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bombaytimes.com/music-runs-in-the-family/articleshow/61602864.cms|title=Music runs in the family|work=BombayTimes|access-date=13 November 2017}}</ref>]]\n\nBorn in Delhi to [[Hindu]] [[Malayali]] parents C. S. Menon and Kunnath Kanakavalli,<ref name=\"daiji\">{{cite web |url= http://www.daijiworld.com/chan/exclusive_arch.asp?ex_id=491|title= A Kandid Konversation with KK|last= Lasrado |first= Richie |date= 25 November 2006| publisher = Daijiworld.com}}</ref> Krishnakumar Kunnath was brought up in New Delhi.<ref name=\"the_hindu_kk_factor\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hindu.com/mp/2005/06/06/stories/2005060600820300.htm| title= The KK factor|last= R|first= Balaji| work= The Hindu | date= 6 June 2005}}</ref> KK sang 3,500 jingles before breaking into [[Bollywood]].<ref name=\"jingle\" /> He is an alumnus of Delhi's [[Mount St Mary's School (New Delhi)|Mount St Mary's School]]<ref name=\"jingle\">{{cite web| url= http://sify.com/movies/bollywood/fullstory.php?id=14884031&cid=2359| title= KK sang 3,500 jingles before Bollywood break| work= Sify movies| date= 28 April 2009| access-date= 7 August 2009| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150412045509/http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/fullstory.php?id=14884031&cid=2359| archive-date= 12 April 2015| url-status= dead}}</ref> and graduated from [[Kirori Mal College]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saavn.com/s/artist/kk-bio/K,5uNVM,qpM_|title=KK|website=saavn.com|access-date=15 December 2017}}</ref> Delhi University. He sang in the \"Josh of India\" song for the support of [[Indian Cricket Team]] during [[Cricket World Cup]] of 1999.<ref name=\"kkworldcup\">{{cite web|url=http://buzz18.in.com/celebrity-profile/kk/2532|title=KK Profile|publisher=[[In.com]]|accessdate=30 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511003811/http://buzz18.in.com/celebrity-profile/kk/2532|archivedate=11 May 2009}}</ref> This song featured members of the Indian Cricket Team\n\nKK married his childhood love Jyothy in 1991.<ref name=\"sensational\">{{cite web| url= http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=28166&n_tit=Mangalore%3A%20Sensational%20Singer%20KK%20to%20Perform%20Live%20in%20City%20on%20Nov%2023| title= Sensational Singer KK to Perform Live in City on Nov 23| work= Daijiworld.com| date= 22 November 2006}}</ref> His son Nakul Krishna Kunnath sang a song \"Masti\" from his latest album [[Humsafar (album)|Humsafar]] with him.<ref name=\"pitch\">{{cite web| url= http://www.screenindia.com/story.php?id=272945&pg=-1| title= High Pitch|first= Rajiv| last= Vijayakar| work= Screen| date= 18 February 2008}}</ref> KK also has a daughter named Tamara Kunnath who, according to KK, loves playing piano. KK says that his family is his source of energy.\n\n== Vocals and musical style ==\n\nKK has been greatly influenced by the singer [[Kishore Kumar]] and music director [[R. D. Burman]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} [[Michael Jackson]], [[Billy Joel]], [[Bryan Adams]] are also favourite international singers of KK.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} KK has said that it is not important for a singer's face to be prominently seen \u2013 saying he believes the important thing is that \"a singer must be heard.\"<ref name=\"A singer must be heard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/8223|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419101735/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/8223|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 April 2015|title= KK Interview with Bollywood Hungama| publisher= [[Bollywood Hungama]]|date= 15 April 2015}}</ref> KK has never undergone any formal training in music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/photo-features/kk-facts-about-the-singer-we-bet-you-dont-know/photostory/48554410.cms|title=KK: Facts about the singer we bet you don\u2019t know|date=2015-08-20|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nAfter graduating from [[Kirori Mal College]], [[Delhi University]] in commerce, KK had a brief stint of eight months as marketing executive in the hotel industry. After few years, in 1994, he moved to [[Mumbai]].<ref name=\"sensational\" />\n\n=== Playback singing ===\n[[File:KK (125).jpg|thumb|Performing Live at The JockeyClub Auditorium, Hong Kong]]\nIn 1994, he gave his demo tape to [[Louis Banks]], [[Ranjit Barot]] and [[Lesle Lewis (composer)|Lesle Lewis]] to get a break in the music arena. He was called by UTV and he sang a jingle for Santogen Suiting ad.<ref name=\"pitch\" /> In a span of four years, he has sung more than 3,500 jingles in 11 Indian languages. He got the first break in Mumbai from UTV to sing jingles.  He considers Lesle Lewis as his mentor for giving him his first jingle to sing in [[Mumbai]].<ref name=\"sensational\" /> KK was introduced as a playback singer with [[A. R. Rahman]]'s hit song \"Kalluri Saaley\" and \"Hello Dr.\" from Kadir's [[Kadhal Desam]] and then \"Strawberry Kannae\" from [[AVM Productions]]'s musical film ''[[Minsara Kanavu]]'' (1997).<ref name=\"Three singers\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2007/03/13/stories/2007031300300600.htm|title=It takes three to tango |newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=13 March 2007}}</ref> [[Pritam Chakraborty]] is also a fan of him.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} He got his Bollywood break  \"Tadap Tadap\" from ''[[Hum Dil De Chuke Sanam]]'' (1999).<ref name=\"Three singers\" /> However, prior to this song he had sung a small portion of the song \"Chhod Aaye Hum\" from Gulzar's Maachis. Till now, KK has sung more than 500 songs in Hindi and more than 200 songs in [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Kannada]] and [[Malayalam]] languages.<ref name=\"on a high note\">{{cite magazine| url= http://www.screenindia.com/old/fullstory.php?content_id=4688|title= On a high note|first= Jhonny| last= D|magazine= [[Screen India]]| date= 4 July 2003}}</ref> He has worked with almost every music director of Hindi film industry active from 1999. He has lent his voice to the biggest hit song of the year 2014 \"Tune Maari Entriyaan\" among several others in [[Gunday]]. KK's new song from the movie [[Bajrangi Bhaijaan]] called \"Tu Jo Mila\" has become popular, many times remained No.1 on [[iTunes]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\nGuinness World Record holder Kumar Sanu who reigned as the top playback singer during the 1990s, has mentioned in several interviews that from the new generation of singers he admires KK. Popular singer [[Arijit Singh]] said he has been inspired by KK in singing, and is a big fan of KK.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Another popular Bollywood singer, [[Ankit Tiwari]] also said he has been greatly influenced by KK and he takes KK as his idol and inspiration.<ref name=\"Dreams in his eyes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/317651/dreams-his-eyes.html |title=Dreams in his eyes |work=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |author=Preeti Verma Lal |date=10 March 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Albums and television ===\n[[File:KK AIIC Jan 2016 2.jpg|thumb|KK Performing Live at Alive India in Concert (Bangalore), Jan 2016]]\nIn 1999, Sony Music had just been launched in India and they were looking to launch a new artiste. KK was selected as the new artiste and he came out with a solo album titled ''[[Pal (album)|Pal]]'' with [[Lesle Lewis (composer)|Lesle Lewis]] composing the music. The album was arranged, composed and produced by [[Lesle Lewis (composer)|Lesle Lewis]] of Colonial Cousins. The lyrics have been penned by [[Mehboob (lyricist)|Mehboob]]. The songs \"Aap Ki Dua\", \"Yaaron\" and the title track \"Pal\" in no time ruled the lips of youngsters & also the music chart. \"Pal\" became an anthem & \"Yaaron\" became friendship anthem. The album just created history. ''Pal'' was the first album released by KK under [[Sony Music]] for which he got the prestigious Screen award as best singer. He is very good friend of Jeevan Deep Prakash\u2014Only resource of OCMC in India )\n\nOn 22 January 2008, KK released his second album ''[[Humsafar (album)|Humsafar]]'' after a gap of eight years.<ref name=\"star\">{{cite magazine| url=http://www.screenindia.com/story.php?id=269294&pg=-1|title= Star-studded music launches are back|magazine= [[Screen India]] | date= 5 February 2008}}</ref> The songs \"Aasman Ke\", \"Dekho Na\", \"Yeh Kahan Mil Gaye Hum\" and \"Rain Bhai Kaari (Maajhi)\" are famous songs from this album. Besides, KK had also sung an English Rock Ballad \"Cineraria\". The title track, \"Humsafar\" is a mix of English and Hindi lyrics. The album ''[[Humsafar (album)|Humsafar]]'' has 10 songs, out of which eight have been composed by KK. The other two songs were taken from his previous album ''Pal''.\n\nKK has also sung many television serial songs like [[Just Mohabbat]], [[Shaka Laka Boom Boom]], Kuch Jhuki Si Palkein, [[Hip Hip Hurray]], kavyanjali, [[Just Dance (Indian TV series)|Just Dance]] . He has also sung the theme song for Star Parivaar Awards 2010 with [[Shreya Ghoshal]]. KK appeared on television too. He was invited as jury member for a talent hunt show [[Fame Gurukul]].<ref name=\"extension\">{{cite web| url= http://sify.com/movies/bollywood/fullstory.php?id=14609691| title= Composing music is an extension of my being:KK| date= 24 February 2008| work= Sify movies.}}</ref>\n\nKK also has sung a song named \"Tanha Chala\" for the Pakistani TV show ''The Ghost'' which was aired on [[Hum TV]] in 2008. The song was composed by Farrukh Abid and Shoiab Farrukh, and [[Momina Duraid]] penned the lyrics.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nKK participated in the latest musical venture of MTV India [[Coke Studio (India)|Coke Studio]]. There he sang one [[qawwali]] \"Chadta Suraj\" along with [[Sabri Brothers]] and a recomposed version of his exquisite track \"Tu Aashiqui Hai\" from movie Jhankaar Beats. He also came in 'Surili Baat' in [[Aaj Tak]] Chanel. He has also performed in [[Sony Mix]] TV Show and [[MTV Unplugged]] Season 3, aired on [[MTV]] 11 January 2014. KK was in [[Dubai]] for his concert 'Salaam Dubai 2014' in April. He also did concerts in Goa, [[Dubai]] & [[Chennai]], and Hong kong.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nOn 29 August 2015, KK appeared in the television singing reality show ''[[Indian Idol Junior]]'' Season 2 to cheer up the emerging singers of [[India]] where he performed \"Khuda Jaane\", \"Mera Pehla Pehla Pyaar\", \"Make Some Noise for the Desi Boyz\", \"Ajab Si\", \"Sach Kehraha Hai Deewana\" and many more songs with the junior idols and \"Tu Aashiqui Hai\" with Vishal Dadlani, \"Aashaayen\" with Salim Merchant and \"Tadap Tadap\" with [[Sonakshi Sinha]]. After 10 years, He appeared in a singing reality show as a judge and guest jury member.\n\nOn 13 September 2015, KK came in \"Baaton Baaton Mein\" on [[Sony Mix]].\n\n== Other projects ==\nIn 2013, KK sang for an international album, ''Rise Up \u2013 Colors of Peace'', which consists of songs written by Turkish poet Fetullah Gulen and sung by artists from 12 countries.  KK recorded a song named \"Rose of My heart\" for the album.\n\nIn 2010, the Indi Band \"Bandish\" produced their second self-titled album. The album has a high energy track in the album Tere Bin \u2013 a rock ballad sung by KK.\n\n== Albums ==\n\nHis debut album ''[[Pal (album)|Pal]]'' was released in April 1999. His performance on the album received a [[Star Screen Award]] from [[Screen India]] for Best Male Singer.<ref name=\"screen award\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/screenawards/award99.html |title=8th Annual Star Screen Awards 1999 |magazine=[[Screen India]] |accessdate=15 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624142340/http://www.screenindia.com/old/screenawards/award99.html |archivedate=24 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nHis second album, [[Humsafar (album)|Humsafar]], was released nine years later, in January 2008. It belongs to the [[pop-rock]] genre and has a total of 10 songs. Humsafar has two songs that are repeated from his earlier album ''Pal'' \u2013 \"Din Ho Ya Raat\" and \"Mehki Hawa\". The video for a romantic song on the album, \"Aasman Ke\", features the singer and [[South Indian people|south Indian]] model [[Suhasi Goradia Dhami]]. \"Humsafar\", the title track, has an interplay of English and [[Hindi]] [[lyrics]] and is about one's conscience and how it is a constant companion in the journey of life. One of the songs, \"Yeh Kahan Mil Gaye Hum\", was penned seven years before the release. \"Dekho Na\", a rock number, was written six years prior. The remaining six songs were developed in the last two years before the release. Other songs in the album include \"Rain Bhai Kaari (Maajhi)\", a mix of Bengali [[Baul]] with rock with a tinge of [[S D Burman]], and \"Cineraria\", a fun-filled English ballad. KK himself wrote the lyrics of \"Cineraria\" and the English part of \"Humsafar\", the title track, while the remaining tracks were written by others.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plain rowheaders\"\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Album(s)\n| length=\"col\" | Music Director(s)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" | Solo Albums\n|-\n| 1999\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Pal (album)|Pal]]''\n| [[Lesle Lewis (composer)|Lesle Lewis]]\n|-\n| 2008\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Humsafar (album)|Humsafar]]''\n| KK\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"  | Compilations\n|-\n| 2002\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Humraaz]]''\n| [[Himesh Reshammiya]]\n|-\n| 2010\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Kavalan\n| KK, Rita{{clarify|date=May 2016}}\n|-\n| 2011\n! ''Soulful Voice KK''\n| Various\n|-\n| 2014\n! ''[[#Now Playing: KK Hits]]''\n| Various\n|-\n| 2013\n! ''KK: Best Of Me''\n| Various\n|-\n| 2015\n! ''Musical Bond: Pritam & KK''\n| [[Pritam Chakraborty]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|List of songs recorded by KK}}\n[[File:Krishna Kumar Kunnath 2009 Crop.jpg|thumb|KK is performing on the stage|KK performing in 2009]]\n\n=== Selected Discography ===\n\n* Tadap Tadap Ke Is Dil Se ''([[Hum Dil De Chuke Sanam]])''\n* Yaaron ''([[Pal (album)]])''\n* Jab Bhi Koi Haseena Dekhu ''([[Hera Pheri (2000 film)|Hera Pheri]])''\n* Koi Kahe Kehta Rahe ''([[Dil Chahta Hai]])''\n* Bardaasht Nahi Kar Sakta ''([[Humraaz]])''\n* Maine Dil Se Kaha ''([[Rog]])''\n* Awarapan Banjarapan ''([[Jism (2003 film)|Jism]])''\n* Ding Dong ''([[Kucch To Hai]])''\n* Kabhi Khusboo ''([[Saaya (2003 film)|Saaya]])\n* Tu Aashiqui Hai ''([[Jhankaar Beats]])''\n* Hai Re Hai Re ''([[Khushi (2003 Hindi film)|Khushi]])''\n* Go Balle Balle ''([[Dil Ne Jise Apna Kahaa]])''\n* Dus Bahane ''([[Dus]])''\n* Bas Ek Pal ''([[Bas Ek Pal]])''\n* Soniye ''([[Aksar]])''\n* Teri Yaadon Mein ''([[The Killer (2006 film)|The Killer]])''\n* Dilnashin Dilnashin ''([[Aashiq Banaya Aapne]])''\n* Aashaayen ''([[Iqbal (film)|Iqbal]])''\n* Tu Hi Meri Shab Hai ''([[Gangster (2006 film)|Gangster]])''\n* Mera Pehla Pehla Pyaar ''([[MP3: Mera Pehla Pehla Pyaar]])''\n* Alvida ''([[Life in A... Metro]])''\n* O Meri Jaan ''([[Life in A... Metro]])''\n* Labon Ko ''([[Bhool Bhulaiyaa]])''\n* Zara Sa ''([[Jannat (film)|Jannat]])''\n* Haan Tu Hai ''([[Jannat (film)|Jannat]])''\n* Tu Mujhe Soch Kabhi ''([[Zindagi Tere Naam]])''\n* Ajab Si ''([[Om Shanti Om]])''\n* Beetein Lamhein ''([[The Train (2007 film)|The Train]])''\n* Khuda Jaane ''([[Bachna Ae Haseeno]])''\n* Dil Ibaadat ''([[Tum Mile]])''\n* Tujhe Sochta Hoon ''([[Jannat 2]])''\n* Zindagi Do Pal Ki ''([[Kites (2010 film)|Kites]])''\n* Dil Kyun Yeh Mera ''([[Kites (2010 film)|Kites]])''\n* Abhi Abhi ''([[Jism 2]])''\n* Tum Ho Mera Pyaar ''([[Haunted \u2013 3D]])''\n* Kya Mujhe Pyaar Hai ''([[Woh Lamhe]])''\n* Main Tera Dhadkan Teri ''([[Ajab Prem Ki Ghazab Kahani]])''\n* Golmaal ''([[Golmaal 3]])''\n* Mujhko Pehchaanlo ''([[Don 2]])''\n* Kaise Bataaoon ''([[3G (film)|3G]])\n* Mat Aazma Re ''([[Murder 3]])''\n* I Am in Love ''([[Once Upon A Time in Mumbai]])''\n* Sajde ''([[Khatta Meetha (2010 film)|Khatta Meetha]])''\n* Tujhi Mein ''([[Crook (film)|Crook]])''\n* Humko Pyaar Hua (Chal Chale) ''([[Ready (2011 film)|Ready]])''\n* Make Some Noise for the Desi Boyz ''([[Desi Boyz]])''\n* Mere Brother Ki Dulhan ''([[Mere Brother Ki Dulhan]])''\n* Tu Jo Mila ''([[Bajrangi Bhaijaan]])''\n* Tu Bhoola Jise ''([[Airlift (2016 film)|Airlift]])''\n* Jannatein Kahan ''([[Jannat 2]])''\n* O Meri Jaan ''([[Tum Mile]])''\n* [[Afreen Afreen]] ''([[1920 London]])''\n* O Meri Jaan ''([[Raaz Reboot]])''\n* Jeetne Ke Liye ''([[Azhar (film)|Azhar]])''\n* Saanson Ke ''([[Raees (film)|Raees]])''\n* Khel Khel Mein ''([[Gold (2018 film)|Gold]])''\n* Haa Tu Hai ''([[Jannat 2]])''\n* Piya Aaye Na'' ([[Aashiqui 2]])''\n* Tum Na Aaye ''([[Badla (2019 film)|Badla]])''\n* Dil Aaj Kal ''([[Purani Jeans]])''\n* Kal Ki Hi Baat Hai ''([[Chhichhore (2019 film)|Chhichhore]])''\n* Feel My Love (Arya in Telugu)\n* Dus Bahane 2.0 ''([[Baaghi 3]])''\n* Aur Tanha ''([[Love Aaj Kal (2020 film)|Love Aaj Kal]])''\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n=== South ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n\n! Award(s)\n\n! Language\n\n! Category\n\n! Result\n|-\n| 2005\n! Hub Awards\n| Tamil\n| Best Playback Singer- Male\n| rowspan=\"1\" {{won}}\n|-\n| 2010\n! Filmfare Awards South\n| Kannada\n| Best Playback Singer- Male\n| rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n! Eenam-Swaralaya Singer of the Year Award\n| Malayalam\n| Singer of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Hindi ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" center | '''\n\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Filmfare Awards]]\n\n|-Won\n| 2000\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Tadap Tadap\" (''[[Hum Dil De Chuke Sanam]]'')\n| rowspan=7 {{nom|Nominated|align=|style=|color=Green}}\n|-\n| 2003\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Bardaasht\" (''[[Humraaz (2002 film)|Humraaz]]'')\n|-\n| 2006\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Dus Bahane\" (''[[Dus (2005 film)|Dus]]'')\n|-\n| 2007\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Tu Hi Meri Shab Hai\" (''[[Gangster (2006 film)|Gangster]]'')\n|-\n| 2008\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Ajab Si\" (''[[Om Shanti Om]]'')\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2009\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Zara Sa\" (''[[Jannat (film)|Jannat]]'')\n|-\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Khuda Jane\" (''[[Bachna Ae Haseeno]]'')\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Screen Awards]]\n|-\n| 1999\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male (Non-Film Music)<ref name=\"screen award\" />\n| \"Pal\" (''[[Pal (album)|Pal]]'')\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2004\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Awarapan Banjarapan\" (''[[Jism (2003 film)|Jism]]'')\n| rowspan=4 {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Tu Aashiqui Hai\" (''[[Jhankaar Beats]]'')\n|-\n| 2006\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Dus Bahane\" (''[[Dus (2005 film)|Dus]]'')\n|-\n| 2007\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Tu Hi Meri Shab Hai\" (''[[Gangster (2006 film)|Gangster]]'')\n|-\n| 2008\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Ajab Si\" (''[[Om Shanti Om]]'')\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Khuda Jaane\" (''[[Bachna Ae Haseeno]]'')\n| {{Won}}\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Zee Cine Awards]]\n|-\n| 2005\n| Best Playback Singer&nbsp;\u2013 Male\n| \"Dus Bahane\" (''[[Dus (2005 film)|Dus]]'')\n| rowspan=4 